.SS "Using Tables in Formulas"
.IX Subsection "Using Tables in Formulas"
Worksheet tables can be added with Excel::Writer::XLSX using the \f(CW\*(C`add_table()\*(C'\fR method:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    worksheet\->add_table(\*(AqB3:F7\*(Aq, {options});
.Ve
.PP
By default tables are named \f(CW\*(C`Table1\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`Table2\*(C'\fR, etc., in the order that they are added. However it can also be set by the user using the \f(CW\*(C`name\*(C'\fR parameter:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    worksheet\->add_table(\*(AqB3:F7\*(Aq, {\*(Aqname\*(Aq: \*(AqSalesData\*(Aq});
.Ve
.PP
If you need to know the name of the table, for example to use it in a formula,
you can get it as follows:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    table = worksheet\->add_table(\*(AqB3:F7\*(Aq);
\&    table_name = table\->{_name};
.Ve
.PP
When used in a formula a table name such as \f(CW\*(C`TableX\*(C'\fR should be referred to as \f(CW\*(C`TableX[]\*(C'\fR (like a Perl array):
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    worksheet\->write_formula(\*(AqA5\*(Aq, \*(Aq=VLOOKUP("Sales", Table1[], 2, FALSE\*(Aq);
.Ve
.SS "Dealing with #NAME? errors"
.IX Subsection "Dealing with #NAME? errors"
If there is an error in the syntax of a formula it is usually displayed in
Excel as \f(CW\*(C`#NAME?\*(C'\fR. If you encounter an error like this you can debug it as
follows:
.IP "1. Ensure the formula is valid in Excel by copying and pasting it into a cell. Note, this should be done in Excel and not other applications such as OpenOffice or LibreOffice since they may have slightly different syntax." 4
.IX Item "1. Ensure the formula is valid in Excel by copying and pasting it into a cell. Note, this should be done in Excel and not other applications such as OpenOffice or LibreOffice since they may have slightly different syntax."
.PD 0
.ie n .IP "2. Ensure the formula is using comma separators instead of semi-colons, see ""Non \s-1US\s0 Excel functions and syntax"" above." 4
.el .IP "2. Ensure the formula is using comma separators instead of semi-colons, see ``Non \s-1US\s0 Excel functions and syntax'' above." 4
.IX Item "2. Ensure the formula is using comma separators instead of semi-colons, see Non US Excel functions and syntax above."
.ie n .IP "3. Ensure the formula is in English, see ""Non \s-1US\s0 Excel functions and syntax"" above." 4
.el .IP "3. Ensure the formula is in English, see ``Non \s-1US\s0 Excel functions and syntax'' above." 4
.IX Item "3. Ensure the formula is in English, see Non US Excel functions and syntax above."
.ie n .IP "4. Ensure that the formula doesn't contain an Excel 2010+ future function as listed in ""Formulas added in Excel 2010 and later"" above. If it does then ensure that the correct prefix is used." 4
.el .IP "4. Ensure that the formula doesn't contain an Excel 2010+ future function as listed in ``Formulas added in Excel 2010 and later'' above. If it does then ensure that the correct prefix is used." 4
.IX Item "4. Ensure that the formula doesn't contain an Excel 2010+ future function as listed in Formulas added in Excel 2010 and later above. If it does then ensure that the correct prefix is used."
.PD
.PP
Finally if you have completed all the previous steps and still get a \f(CW\*(C`#NAME?\*(C'\fR error you can examine a valid Excel file to see what the correct syntax should be. To do this you should create a valid formula in Excel and save the file. You can then examine the \s-1XML\s0 in the unzipped file.
.PP
The following shows how to do that using Linux \f(CW\*(C`unzip\*(C'\fR and libxml's xmllint
<http://xmlsoft.org/xmllint.html> to format the \s-1XML\s0 for clarity:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    $ unzip myfile.xlsx \-d myfile
\&    $ xmllint \-\-format myfile/xl/worksheets/sheet1.xml | grep \*(Aq<f>\*(Aq
\&
\&            <f>SUM(1, 2, 3)</f>
.Ve
.SS "Formula Results"
.IX Subsection "Formula Results"
Excel::Writer::XLSX doesn't calculate the result of a formula and instead stores the value 0 as the formula result. It then sets a global flag in the \s-1XLSX\s0 file to say that all formulas and functions should be recalculated when the file is opened.
.PP
This is the method recommended in the Excel documentation and in general it works fine with spreadsheet applications. However, applications that don't have a facility to calculate formulas will only display the 0 results. Examples of such applications are Excel Viewer, \s-1PDF\s0 Converters, and some mobile device applications.
.PP
If required, it is also possible to specify the calculated result of the
formula using the optional last \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR parameter in \f(CW\*(C`write_formula\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    worksheet\->write_formula(\*(AqA1\*(Aq, \*(Aq=2+2\*(Aq, num_format, 4);
.Ve
.PP
The \f(CW\*(C`value\*(C'\fR parameter can be a number, a string, a boolean sting (\f(CW\*(AqTRUE\*(Aq\fR or \f(CW\*(AqFALSE\*(Aq\fR) or one of the following Excel error codes:
.PP
.Vb 7
\&    #DIV/0!
\&    #N/A
\&    #NAME?
\&    #NULL!
\&    #NUM!
\&    #REF!
\&    #VALUE!
.Ve
.PP
It is also possible to specify the calculated result of an array formula created with \f(CW\*(C`write_array_formula\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    # Specify the result for a single cell range.
\&    worksheet\->write_array_formula(\*(AqA1:A1\*(Aq, \*(Aq{=SUM(B1:C1*B2:C2)}\*(Aq, format, 2005);
.Ve
.PP
However, using this parameter only writes a single value to the upper left cell in the result array. For a multi-cell array formula where the results are required, the other result values can be specified by using \f(CW\*(C`write_number()\*(C'\fR to write to the appropriate cell:
.PP
.Vb 4
\&    # Specify the results for a multi cell range.
\&    worksheet\->write_array_formula(\*(AqA1:A3\*(Aq, \*(Aq{=TREND(C1:C3,B1:B3)}\*(Aq, format, 15);
\&    worksheet\->write_number(\*(AqA2\*(Aq, 12, format);
\&    worksheet\->write_number(\*(AqA3\*(Aq, 14, format);
.Ve
.SH "WORKING WITH VBA MACROS"
.IX Header "WORKING WITH VBA MACROS"
An Excel \f(CW\*(C`xlsm\*(C'\fR file is exactly the same as a \f(CW\*(C`xlsx\*(C'\fR file except that is includes an additional \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR file which contains functions and/or macros. Excel uses a different extension to differentiate between the two file formats since files containing macros are usually subject to additional security checks.
.PP
The \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR file is a binary \s-1OLE COM\s0 container. This was the format used in older \f(CW\*(C`xls\*(C'\fR versions of Excel prior to Excel 2007. Unlike all of the other components of an xlsx/xlsm file the data isn't stored in \s-1XML\s0 format. Instead the functions and macros as stored as pre-parsed binary format. As such it wouldn't be feasible to define macros and create a \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR file from scratch (at least not in the remaining lifespan and interest levels of the author).
.PP
Instead a workaround is used to extract \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR files from existing xlsm files and then add these to Excel::Writer::XLSX files.
.SS "The extract_vba utility"
.IX Subsection "The extract_vba utility"
The \f(CW\*(C`extract_vba\*(C'\fR utility is used to extract the \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR binary from an Excel 2007+ xlsm file. The utility is included in the Excel::Writer::XLSX bin directory and is also installed as a standalone executable file:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    $ extract_vba macro_file.xlsm
\&    Extracted: vbaProject.bin
.Ve
.SS "Adding the \s-1VBA\s0 macros to a Excel::Writer::XLSX file"
.IX Subsection "Adding the VBA macros to a Excel::Writer::XLSX file"
Once the \f(CW\*(C`vbaProject.bin\*(C'\fR file has been extracted it can be added to the Excel::Writer::XLSX workbook using the \f(CW\*(C`add_vba_project()\*(C'\fR method:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    $workbook\->add_vba_project( \*(Aq./vbaProject.bin\*(Aq );
.Ve
.PP
If the \s-1VBA\s0 file contains functions you can then refer to them in calculations using \f(CW\*(C`write_formula\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    $worksheet\->write_formula( \*(AqA1\*(Aq, \*(Aq=MyMortgageCalc(200000, 25)\*(Aq );
.Ve
.PP
Excel files that contain functions and macros should use an \f(CW\*(C`xlsm\*(C'\fR extension or else Excel will complain and possibly not open the file:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    my $workbook  = Excel::Writer::XLSX\->new( \*(Aqfile.xlsm\*(Aq );
.Ve
.PP
It is also possible to assign a macro to a button that is inserted into a
worksheet using the \f(CW\*(C`insert_button()\*(C'\fR method:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    my $workbook  = Excel::Writer::XLSX\->new( \*(Aqfile.xlsm\*(Aq );
\&    ...
\&    $workbook\->add_vba_project( \*(Aq./vbaProject.bin\*(Aq );
\&
\&    $worksheet\->insert_button( \*(AqC2\*(Aq, { macro => \*(Aqmy_macro\*(Aq } );
.Ve
.PP
It may be necessary to specify a more explicit macro name prefixed by the workbook \s-1VBA\s0 name as follows:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    $worksheet\->insert_button( \*(AqC2\*(Aq, { macro => \*(AqThisWorkbook.my_macro\*(Aq } );
.Ve
.PP
See the \f(CW\*(C`macros.pl\*(C'\fR from the examples directory for a working example.
.PP
Note: Button is the only \s-1VBA\s0 Control supported by Excel::Writer::XLSX. Due to the large effort in implementation (1+ man months) it is unlikely that any other form elements will be added in the future.
.SS "Setting the \s-1VBA\s0 codenames"
.IX Subsection "Setting the VBA codenames"
\&\s-1VBA\s0 macros generally refer to workbook and worksheet objects. If the \s-1VBA\s0 codenames aren't specified then Excel::Writer::XLSX will use the Excel defaults of \f(CW\*(C`ThisWorkbook\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`Sheet1\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`Sheet2\*(C'\fR etc.
.PP
If the macro uses other codenames you can set them using the workbook and worksheet \f(CW\*(C`set_vba_name()\*(C'\fR methods as follows:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&      $workbook\->set_vba_name( \*(AqMyWorkbook\*(Aq );
\&      $worksheet\->set_vba_name( \*(AqMySheet\*(Aq );
.Ve
.PP
You can find the names that are used in the \s-1VBA\s0 editor or by unzipping the \f(CW\*(C`xlsm\*(C'\fR file and grepping the files. The following shows how to do that using libxml's xmllint <http://xmlsoft.org/xmllint.html> to format the \s-1XML\s0 for clarity:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    $ unzip myfile.xlsm \-d myfile
\&    $ xmllint \-\-format \`find myfile \-name "*.xml" | xargs\` | grep "Pr.*codeName"
\&
\&      <workbookPr codeName="MyWorkbook" defaultThemeVersion="124226"/>
\&      <sheetPr codeName="MySheet"/>
.Ve
.PP
Note: This step is particularly important for macros created with non-English versions of Excel.
.SS "What to do if it doesn't work"
.IX Subsection "What to do if it doesn't work"
This feature should be considered experimental and there is no guarantee that it will work in all cases. Some effort may be required and some knowledge of \s-1VBA\s0 will certainly help. If things don't work out here are some things to try:
.IP "\(bu" 4
Start with a simple macro file, ensure that it works and then add complexity.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Try to extract the macros from an Excel 2007 file. The method should work with macros from later versions (it was also tested with Excel 2010 macros). However there may be features in the macro files of more recent version of Excel that aren't backward compatible.
.IP "\(bu" 4
Check the code names that macros use to refer to the workbook and worksheets (see the previous section above). In general \s-1VBA\s0 uses a code name of \f(CW\*(C`ThisWorkbook\*(C'\fR to refer to the current workbook and the sheet name (such as \f(CW\*(C`Sheet1\*(C'\fR) to refer to the worksheets. These are the defaults used by Excel::Writer::XLSX. If the macro uses other names then you can specify these using the workbook and worksheet \f(CW\*(C`set_vba_name()\*(C'\fR methods:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&      $workbook>set_vba_name( \*(AqMyWorkbook\*(Aq );
\&      $worksheet\->set_vba_name( \*(AqMySheet\*(Aq );
.Ve
